lk surname <b>Naunton</b>, a habitational name from Naunton Hall in Rendlesham and possibly also Naughton (both in Suffolk). The latter may derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Nagli</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":12,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705201,"age":106,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":115,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Nanton was born in 1443, in Hertfordshire, England, his father, George Nanton, was 33 and his mother, Lady Catherine de Windsor, was 23. He married Hermione Billard-Nessie in 1473, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in Herefordshire, England."},"et":{"1443–":"1443–Surnud","1443–Male":"1443–Surnud","1450–1503":"1450–1503","1445–1479":"1445–1479","1473–1524":"1473–1524","1476–Male":"1476–Surnud","1479–Male":"1479–Surnud","1481–Male":"1481–Surnud","1410–1490":"1410–1490","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1473":"1473","abt 1481":"umbes 1481","1450":"1450","1481":"1481","1490":"1490","abt 1476":"umbes 1476","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1524":"1524","abt 1479":"umbes 1479","1479":"1479","1500":"1500","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1549":"1549","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1443–":"1443–Kuollut","1443–Male":"1443–Kuollut","1450–1503":"1450–1503","1445–1479":"1445–1479","1473–1524":"1473–1524","1476–Male":"1476–Kuollut","1479–Male":"1479–Kuollut","1481–Ma